Phenotype (for reference): renal cell carcinoma; pancreatic endocrine tumor
Evidence Statements: A 40-year-old woman was found with clear cell renal cell carcinoma and pancreatic endocrine tumours. Genetic analysis revealed a germline mutation c.499C>T (p.Arg167Trp) in the VHL gene. The patient had negative family history for VHL disease but the paper did not describe if maternal and/or paternal genotype was tested. ACMG: PM1, PP4
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Phenotype (for reference): hemangioblastoma; endolymphatic sac tumor; epididymal cyst; pancreatic cysts; renal cyst; renal cell carcinoma
Notes: mutation not confirmed in parents = evidence for de novo mutation
Evidence Statements: A 33Y male presented with bilateral muliple renal cell carcinomas, medullary hemangioblastoma, endolymphatic sac tumor, epididymis cyst, pancreatic cysts and renal cysts. Genetic evaluation revealed a deletion of exon 3 in the VHL gene, confirming the diagnosis of VHL disease. Family history was unremarkable, and both parents tested negative for the mutation, suggesting the mutation occurred de novo in the patient. ACMG: PVS1, PS2, PP4
Warnings: NM_000551.3:c.464-?_642+?del: char 18: expected a digit

Notes: Proband. Review this paper, references 30-38 have pts with same mutation. Review p2p and paternal family
Evidence Statements: The authors evaluated a proband (male) with a heterozygous compound mutation p.Pro81Ser;p.Pro2Pro and early-onest renal cell carcinoma at 29Y old. Four family members on the maternal side tested positive as c.241C>T (p.Pro81Ser) carriers, with no VHL-related phenotypes. The proband's mother did have breast cancer at 34 Y old and was 52Y old at the time of the study. The proband had a 2Y old daughter with only the p.Pro2Pro mutation and no phenotypes. The paternal family members were not available for genetic testing, but members had the following phenotypes: father died at 56Y from bladder cancer in situ (he was a smoker), uncle died at 46Y from renal cell carcinoma (he was a smoker), aunt had cervix cancer at 46Y old, niece was 23Y old and born with one kindey, 2 other aunts (60Y and 52Y) had diabetes mellitus type 2, and grandma diead at 77Y from ventricular cancer. We are not able to tell if the p.Pro2Pro synonymous variant was de novo or inherited from the paternal side. The paper also looked at in silico analysis for the p.Pro81Ser mutation and found the variant was predicted as tolerated by SIFT, Mutation Taster and Polyphen but was predicted to affect the protein function by HOPE and Symphony. RCC tissue analysis from the proband revealed lack of pVHL expression in the tumor tissue. ACMG PP4 PP3

Phenotype (for reference): hemangioblastoma; retinal capillary hemangioma; pheochromocytoma; renal cell carcinoma; pancreatic cysts
Notes: could be repeated in 9829912... (older family members)
Evidence Statements: A 68Y male patient presented with CNS haemangioblastoma, retinal haemangioblastoma, renal cell carcinoma, and serous cystadenoma. At 74Y he developed phaeochromocytoma. Genetic testing confirmed a mutation c.245G>C (p.Arg82Pro) in the VHL gene which was confirmed in 3 other family members. One was his grandson which was asymptomatic, his son that had renal cell carcinoma and pancreatic cysts or serous cystadenoma, and a distant relative had CNS hemangioblastoma, renal cell carcinoma, symptomatic phaeochromocytoma, and pancreatic cysts/serous cystadenoma. 4 other relatives had CHS hemangioblastoma but were not confirmed for the mutation. ACMG: PP2, PP1, PP4

Phenotype (for reference): retinal capillary hemangioma; cerebellar hemangioblastoma; renal cell carcinoma
Evidence Statements: A 45Y male patient presented with a history of bilateral retinal angiomas, multifocal cerebellar hemangioblastomas, and bilateral renal cell carcinoma was found to have a c.473T>A (p.Leu158Gln) germline mutation in the VHL gene. His 30Y nephew was confirmed with this mutation and had a similar phenotype indicating VHL 1 disease. 2 of the patient's brothers also presented with VHL 1, although their exact phenotype was not described and their genotype was not confirmed. ACMG: PP2, PP1, PP4 They were also found with c.340+5G>C, a previouslt reported benign variant.

Phenotype (for reference): pheochromocytoma; paraganglioma; diabetes; hypertension; Adrenal pheochromocytoma; Obesity; Obstructive sleep apnea; Muscle fiber hypertrophy; Hematuria; Abnormality of the urinary system
Evidence Statements: A 53-year-old man of Puerto-Rican descent was found with a c.524A>G (p.Tyr175Cys) germline missense mutation in the VHL gene, and presented with bilateral pheochromocytoma and paraganglioma within the paracaval lymph node. His diabetes and hypertension resolved after the surgery. Family history was not presented. AMCG: PP2, PP4

Notes: more info in 15607616 ... Hospital de Niños Ricardo Gutiérrez has 255 patients with pheo studied over 40 years; pta had 2A, can assume pheo and hemangioblastoma?
Evidence Statements: The aim of this study was to establish the characteristics of pheochromocytoma in a population of 58 patients between 4 and 20 years of age studied at Hospital de Niños Ricardo Gutiérrez. They represented a 23% of the total population of 255 pheochromocytoma patients studied. Two children belonging to the same family had VHL type 2A and presented the frequent mutation Arg167Trp. Specific phenotypes besides pheochromocytoma were not described. ACMG: PM1 PP4

Evidence Statements: Patients with ELSTs in the VHL registries of the participating centers in Europe were identified and included in the International Endolymphatic Sac Tumor Registry. The statistics of this registry is as follows: mean age 30, 62% female, 91% symptomatic, 54% retinal angioma, CNS hemangioblastoma 72%, renal cell carcinoma 46%, pheochromocytoma 19%, pancreatic neuroendocrine tumour(12%). Only endolymphatic sac tumours can be confirmed as a phenotype for this mutation, which was found in 1 individual from France.

Evidence Statements: A case report of a 34Y women genetically confirmed with c.500G>A (p.Arg167Gln) in the VHL gene and type 2A VHL disease presented with 2 CNS hemangioblastomas (brain and spinal cord), left pheochromocytoma, pancreatic neuroendocrine tumours, and a parotid tumour. Patient had a postive family history, with her mother and children having VHL disease; no additional information on phenotype and genotype for family members was provided. Patient had a somatic Thr105Met mutation in the parotid tumour in addition to the germline mutation. ACMG: PM1, PP1, PP4
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Notes: N/A; how to record general "mother and children had VHL" in data sheet
Evidence Statements: The patient was a 42 year old female who first presented for assessment of a right-sided neck mass that had been causing discomfort for 3 months. Further testing found unilateral adrenal pheochromocytoma (left adrenal), central nervous system hemangioblastoma (brain), central nervous system hemangioblastoma (spinal cord), two small pancreatic neuroendocrine tumours, and a parotid tumour. Genetic testing confirmed a familial missense mutation at c.500G>C of the VHL gene. She was diagnosed with type 2A VHL. Her mother and children are reported to have VHL but genotype and phenotypes are not described. ACMG: PP4

Evidence Statements: This patient was a twelve year old male who presented with complaints of weight loss, hot flushes, palpitation and diaphoresis. Further testing found a bilateral pheochromocytoma, pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor, intermittent fever, blood pressure level of 160/100mmHg, and a heart rate of 110 beats per minute. Genetic testing confirmed a germline missense mutation at c.482G>A of the VHL gene. He has a negative family history. ACMG: PP2, PS2, PP4.

Phenotype (for reference): retinal capillary hemangioblastoma; pancreatic cysts; muscle weakness; Myalgia; Myoglobinuria
Evidence Statements: A male patient born to consanguineous parents was found with a c.256C>G (p.Pro86Ala) mutation in the VHL gene at 10 years old. He went on to develop bilateral retinal capillary hemangioblastomas and multiple pancreatic cysts. He also presented with weakness, muscular algias, and myoblobinurina which is consistent with a homozygous c.338C>T(p.Ser113Leu) mutation found in his CPT2 gene. Genetic analysis revealed the VHL mutation in other family members, but not the CPT2 mutation. Patient's mother, mathernal grandmother, 2 maternal aunts, brother, and cousin were confirmed for the VHL mutation. The cousin was found to be an asymptomatic carrier. Mother presented with SNC hemangioblastoma, renal cysts, pancreatic neuroendocrine tumour, and retinal capillary hemangioblastoma. Maternal grandmother presented with SNC hemangioblastoma, renal cysts, pancreatic neuroendocrine tumour, and tympanic paraganglioma. One maternal aunt had SNC hemangioblastoma, retinal capillary hemabgioblastoma, and a pancreatic neuroendocrine tumour,and hte other aunt had SNC hemangioblastoma, renal cysts, pancreatic cysts, pancreatic neuroendocrine tumour, retinal capillary hemangioblastoma and a endolymphatic sac tumor. Finally, the patient's brother presented with pheochromocytoma and epydidimal cysts. ACMG:PP2, PP1, PP4

Evidence Statements: A 36Y male patient underwent right adrenalectomy for a reoccuring pheochromocytoma. The first occurance of pheochromocytoma was at 12Y. The patient passed 2 days after the procedure and an autopsy confirmed more specific manifestations of VHL disease: 3 hemangioblastomas in the floor of the fourth ventricle, in the superficial dorsal right side of the thoracic spinal cord, and in a left lumbar dorsal-nerve root, renal cysts, pancreatic neuroendocrine tumour, and liver hemangiomas. Genetic testing confirmed a germline VHL mutation c.500G>A (p.Arg167Gln). Familial testing showed that this mutation was inhertied from the mother, who had bilateral renal cysts at 58Y. ACMG: PM1, PP4, PP1
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Evidence Statements: A Japanese family with Type 2A VHL disease was studied. Proband was a 25 year old male, who first presented with right pheochromocytoma at age 13, CNS hemangioblastoma and left pheochromocytoma at age 18, and left retinal hemangioblastoma at age 22. Patient's brother presented with CNS hemangioblastoma, retinal hemangioblastoma, bilateral pheochromocytoma and pancreatic tumour. Patient's father presented with CNS hemangioblastoma, retinal hemangioblastoma, unilateral pheochromocytoma, and pancreatic tumour. The same germline mutation (c.392A>G) subsituting Asn with Ser at amino acid 131 was confirmed for the patient and brother. The mutation was not confirmed for the father. Evidence Statements: A 17-year-old female was referred for paroxysmal supraventricular tachycardia and anemia. She was diagnosed with a left adrenal pheochromocytoma. A left adrenalectomy was performed. Six months after surgery, histopathologic findings of thoracoscopic lung biopsy specimens confirmed metastasis of the malignant pheochromocytoma. Genetic testing confirmed a novel missense mutation at codon 194 (V194G) in exon 3 of the VHL gene, which was inherited from the paternal allele, and a loss of heterozygosity was noted in 3 of the patient's distinct tumors. Two independent in silico analyses suggested that this amino acid substitution was pathogenic. ACMG: PP2, PP4

Evidence Statements: A retrospective study reviewed cases of 23 patients with advanced and complicated VHL eye disease who underwent pars plana vitrectomy in the years 1999 to 2012 that were a part of 223 VHL patients consulted at the International Hereditary Cancer Center and Polish VHL Registry. A 21 year old with a germline c.233A>T transversion results in a p.Asn78Ile protein change with previous history of HbCNS, ELST, and renal cell carcinoma. Patient was examined in a study of advanced VHL eye disease and had multiple retinal capillary hemangioblastomas requiring surgery.

Notes:
Twenty-three patients who were part of a 223 VHL patient cohort from the International Hereditgary Cancer Center and Polish VHL registry who underwent surgery for advanced VHL eye disease were
 assessed by genetic tests, diagnostic tests for systemic lesions, and clinical eye examination. 24 patients were identified requiring surgery for advanced VHL-associated eye disease, all of whom presented with retinal capillary hemangioblastomas. All but one also presented with other systemic CNS hemangioblastomas (23/24), as well as other manifestations such as renal cell carcinoma (11/24), PNET (2/24), pheochromocytoma (1/24), and ELST (2/24). Numerous VHL mutations were identified, including substitutions and deletions.
Evidence Statements: A retrospective study reviewed cases of 23 patients with advanced and complicated VHL eye disease who underwent pars plana vitrectomy in the years 1999 to 2012 that were a part of 223 VHL patients consulted at the International Hereditary Cancer Center and Polish VHL Registry. An 11 year old with a germline c.446delG deletion resulting in a frameshift with a previous history of HbCNS. The patient had multiple retinal capillary hemangioblastomas requiring surgery.

Phenotype (for reference): pancreatic cysts; renal cell carcinoma; cerebellar hemangioblastoma
Evidence Statements: A 39-year-old man presented with bilateral clear cell renal cell carcinoma. Bilateral nephron sparing surgery was performed. After 2 years multiple pancreatic cysts were noted. Two years later 6 bilateral renal cell carcinoma lesions developed that were up to 4 cm. in diameter. Repeat bilateral nephron sparingsurgery was performed. Five years later at age 48 years, evaluation revealed cerebellar hemangioblastoma. Deoxyibonucleic acid analysis of the peripheral blood demonstrated a missense germline mutation of the von Hippel-Lindau gene v.486C>G (p.Cys162Trp). Family history was unremarkable and the patient was childless. ACMG: PP2, PS2, PP4
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Phenotype (for reference): hemangioblastoma; retinal capillary hemangioma; renal cell carcinoma; Abnormality of the pancreas
Evidence Statements: Direct sequencing and multiplex ligation dependent probe amplification were performed on thirteen unrelated subjects with VHL mutations. The clinical manifestations and family histories of the subjects were evaluated. A 49 year old Korean male patient presented with central nervous system hemangioblatoma at age 49, retinal hemangioblastoma at age 64, bilateral renal cell carcinoma at age 51, and multiple pancreatic lesions at age 64. Genetic testing confirmed a familial frameshift mutation at c.160_161delAT of the VHL gene. The patient has a 38 year old son and a 35 year old daughter confirmed with the same mutation that have very similar manifestations. ACMG: PVS1, PP4, PP1

A 32 year old Korean male patient presented with central nervous system hemangioblastoma at age 32, retinal hemangioblastoma at age 44, bilateral renal cell carcinoma at age 44, and multiple pancreatic lesions at age 41. Genetic testing confirmed a familial deletion mutation involving the deletion of exons 2 and 3 of the VHL gene. The patient has a son with the same mutations but no symptoms, a 29 year old brother with the same mutation and same symptoms, and an 18 year old nephew with the same symptoms, but an unconfirmed mutation. ACMG: PVS1, PP4, PP1

Evidence Statements: A retrospective cohort study was conducted at a public children’s hospital (Buenos Aires, Argentina). Eligible patients were all index cases with clinical diagnosis or clinical suspicion of type 1 VHL referred to the Centro de Investigaciones Endocrinologicas ‘‘Dr. Cesar Bergada,’’ Hospital de Ninos ‘‘Dr. Ricardo Gutierrez,’’ for genetic testing from 2003 to 2015. A nonsense germline mutation c.481C>T at the VHL gene subsituted Arg at amino acid 161 with a premature stop codon. This mutation was confirmed in 4 patients. Patient (#1) had been clinically diagnosed with type 1 VHL at age 13, and presented with retinal angioma (16Y) and endolymphatic sac tumours (13Y). No remarkable family history. This mutation was also confirmed in patient#3: diagnosed with VHL with genetic testing confirming this VHL mutation when they were 20Y. They presented with CNS hemangioblastoma at 20Y, 25Y, 26Y, clear cell renal cancer at 27Y, pancreatic cysts at 25Y, renal cysts at 25Y, and epididymal cysts at 31Y. There was no remarkable family history. Patient #4: Genetically confirmed for the mutation at 21Y and presented with CNS hemangioblastoma at 22Y, retinal angioma at 21Y, pancreatic cysts at 23Y, and epididymal cysts since birth. No family history for VHL. Patient #9: Genetically confirmed for the mutation at 25Y and presented with CNS hemangioblastoma at 22Y, clear cell renal cell carcinoma at 22Y, renal cysts at 22Y, and pancreatic cysts at 22Y. No family history for VHL. ACMG: PP2, PS2
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Evidence Statements: The patient cohort consisted of 57 patients from Southern Italy with hemangioblastoma: 6 were syndromic and 51 were apparently sporadic. The patient material was obtained at the Department of Neurosurgery and Medical Genetics Service of the IRCCS ‘‘Casa Sollievo della Sofferenza’’ Hospital (San Giovanni Rotondo, Italy) between 1992 and 2011. Genetic analysis found a germline 4 kb deletion encompassing exon 1-2 region of the VHL gene in Patient HGB-51. Patient HGB-51 was classified with a VHL-associated cerebellar hemangioblastoma diagnosed at 17Y old, they were followed-up for two years. Evidence Statements: A retrospective cohort study included all the VHL patients diagnosed at Peking University First Hospital (Beijing, China) prior to June 1 2016. A total of 291 patients from 115 different families were included for analysis. Ten unrelated probands were genetically confirmed with this germlin emutation. The first proband was a male from family #190 who was diagnosed with renal cell carcinoma at 22Y, Pmultiple pancreatic lesions at 22Y, and pheochromocytoma at 22Y. The second proband was a male from family #91 who was diagnosed with CNS hemangioblastoma at 25Y and retinal angioma at 14Y. His sister was diagnosed with multiple pancreatic lesions at 28Y. The third proband was a female from family #92 who was diagnosed with CNS hemangioblastoma at 39Y, renal cell carcinoma at 39Y, and multiple pancreatic tumors at 36Y. The fourth proband was a male from family #93 who was diagnosed with retinal angioma at 18Y, renal cell carcinoma at 18Y, and multiple pancreatic lesions at 16Y. HIs mother, who was not genetically confirmed with the mutation, was diagnosed with renal cell carcinoma at 43Y and multiple pancreatic lesions at 43Y. The fifth proband was a male from family #94 who was diagnosed with CNS haemangioblastoma at 28Y, retinal angioma at 41Y, renal cell carcinoma at 40Y, multpile pancreatic lesions at 40Y, and pheochromocytoma at 40Y. His daughter who is of unknown age is asymptomatic. The sixth proband is a female from family #95 who was diagnosed with CNS haemangioblastoma at 18Y, renal cell carcinoma at 31Y, and multiple pancreatic lesions at 31Y. Her daughter who is of unknown age is asymptomatic. Her sister was diagnosed with renal cell carcinoma at 44Y. Her nephew (son of sister) who is of unknown age is asymptomatic. The seventh proband is a male from family #96 who was diagnosed with CNS hemangioblastoma at 23Y, retinal angioma at 17Y, and multiple pancreatic lesions at 19Y. His mother was diagnosed with CNS haemangioblastoma at 43Y, retinal angioma at 35Y, renal cell carcinoma at 44Y, and multiple pancreatic lesions at 44Y. The eighth proband was a male from family #97 who was diagnosed with CNS haemangioblastoma at 46Y, retinal angioma at 46Y, renal cell carcinoma at 46Y, and multiple pancreatic lesions at 46Y. The ninth proband was a female from family #98 who was diagnosed with CNS hemangioblastoma at 27Y, renal cell carcinoma at 27Y, and multiple pancreatic lesions at 27Y. Her father of unknown age is asymptomatic. Her grandmother, who was not genetically confirmed with the mutation, was diagnosed with renal cell carcinoma at 60Y and multiple pancreatic lesions at 27Y. The tenth proband was a female from family #99 who was diagnosed with CNS haemangioblastoma at 31Y, renal cell carcinoma at 32Y, and multiple pancreatic lesions at 32Y. Her mother, who was not genetically confirmed with the mutation, was diagnosed with CNS hemangioblastoma at 29Y. Her uncle, who was not genetically confirmed with the mutation, was diagnosed with CNS hemangioblastoma at 28Y and renal cell carcinoma at 50Y.

Evidence Statements: A case report reveals a 3Y girl with right adrenal malignant pheochromocytoma, with the mother diagnosed with von Hippel-Lindau syndrome. The mother was 38Y and diagnosed with bilateral pheochromocytoma that was resected when she was 18Y. She presented several relapses, the most recent one at 32Y. At 32Y she was also diagnosed with cerebral angioma. Genetic tests revealed the presence of the VHL c 244 C>G (p. Arg 82 Gly) heterozygote mutation in the mother, as well as in the child. After 6 months from the complete resection of the tumor, the patient is without any clinical symptoms, with normal blood pressure, normal ophthalmoscopy, no tumor markers and no evidence of tumor on cerebral or abdominal MRI.

Evidence Statements: Case studies of three familes affected by VHL and their children was described. This missense mutation was found in Family 1 of 5 members. The father was 48Y when he was found to have renal cell carcinoma and bilateral pheochromocytoma. He died one year after diagnosis despite chemotherapy treatments. His son was diagnosed with and treated for bilateral pheochromocytoma at 13Y and endolymphatic sac tumours at 19Y. The son had a sister who tested postive for the mutation although her phenotype is not described. It is unclear whether the mother and the second son were negative for the mutation or were not tested.

Evidence Statements: A case report of a 32 year old male patient presenting with bilateral retinal hemangioblastoma, loss of vision in the left eye, and a history of cerebral hemangioblastoma 8 years prior (when patient was 24 years old) revealed a c.481C>T mutation in the VHL gene, leading to the subsquent protien change Arg161*. 2 family members (daughter and sister) were confirmed with the c.481C>T mutation. Patient's 12 year old daughter had no clinical presentations. Patient's sister had an optic nerve head hemangioblastoma in the left eye, peripheral temporal retina hemangioblastoma in left eye, and cystic lesions in the pancreas and kidney. Patient recalled mother having advanced unilateral vision loss and dying due to renal cancer. Genetic confirmation for mother is not availiable. ACMG codes: PP2, PP1, PP4

Evidence Statements: A case report showed that a 7-year-old girl presented with decreased vision in both eyes for 1 month. Examination showed visual acuity of 20/50 and 20/60, no afferent pupillary defect, cecocentral scotomas, and bilateral optic disc edema with extensive peripapillary and macular exudates. Magnetic resonance imaging showed multiple cortical and subcortical white matter lesions. The patient was lost to follow-up until age 18 when she developed shortness of breath and was found to have multiple pulmonary metastases identified as pheochromocytoma by biopsy. Genetic testing identified a 3p25-26 (c.482 G>A) VHL gene chromosomal mutation consistent with von Hippel-Lindau disease genotype. Multiple peripheral retinal vascular dilations and small retinal capillary hemangioblastomas were also found. Her past medical history and family history were negative for eye disease, renal cell carcinoma, or neurologic syndromes. ACMG: PP2, PS2, PP4

Notes: white; parents to be screened for VHL
Evidence Statements: 3-year-old white male child presented with renal cell carcinoma. Genetic testing confirmed 2 mutations: a translocation between chromosome X and 1 t(X;1)(p11.2; p34.3). A germline missense mutation was found c.562C>G (p.Leu188Val) in the VHL gene. Genotype of parents were not yet available. ACMG: PP2, PP4
Warnings: ;UNKNOWN is not part of genome build GRCh37

Evidence Statements: A germline translocation t(1;3)(q32;q13.3) was identified by karyotyping in five members of the family including all three renal cell carcinoma cases tested: 56Y male with bilateral ccrenal cell carcinoma, his 62Y male cousin with ccrenal cell carcinoma, his 79Y aunt with left ccrenal cell carcinoma and multiple lung metastases, and his mom and daughter who were both carriers. There were two other family members who died from non-renal cancer. III.5 died of gastric cancer at the age of 49 and III.7 died of exocrine pancreatic cancer at the age of 60. Genotyping was not available for either. Genotyping was not availble for his uncle and aunt, who had ccrenal cell carcinoma and was expected to be a VHL mutation carrier, respectively. ACMG: PVS1, PP1, PP4

 C-cell tumors, one MTC and one CCH, Extra-adrenal pheochromocytoma occurred in

Evidence Statements: Nine individuals from 2 different families were found to have a missense mutation (c.562C>G) subsituting leucine with valine at amino acid 259. All 9 patients had pheochromocytma, 2 of the 9 patients also had thyroid C-cell tumors, one had medullary thyroid carcinoma, and one had C-cell hyperplasia. Three of the 9 patients also developed extra-adrenal pheochromocytoma. ACMG: PP2, PP1, PP4

Notes: germline mutation C>A in the -1 position of the exon 3 splice acceptor sequence
Evidence Statements: Patient #1 in a case series reported with HP:0030393, HP:0002666, spinal hemanioblastoma; HP:0001737. The patient was 32Y and female; genetic analysis confirmed a germline mutation C>A in the -1 position of the exon 3 splice acceptor sequence. The mutation was found in her father and 2 sons who had VHL symptoms (undescribed). A splice mutation may suggest PVS1 and cosegreation wtith multiple affected family members may suggest PP1. The index patient's phenotypes are highly specific to VHL disease (PP4).

Evidence Statements: Medical records of 26 patients with germline mutations of the VHL gene who had been diagnosed with VHL disease in Severance Hospital (Seoul, Republic of Korea) and Samsung Medical Center (Seoul, Republic of Korea) between 2003 and 2012 were respectively reviewed. One 43Y male patient presented with retinal hemangioblastoma and central nervous system hemangioblastoma. He had a germline missense mutation in the VHL gene (c.568T>C; Phe190Leu). The patient had a positive family history of VHL disease.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Notes: family history was not significant for tumor occurrence
Evidence Statements: This patient was a 10 year old girl who presented with intermittent fever. Further testing found a bilateral pheochromocytoma, pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor, blood pressure level of 160/100mmHg and a heart rate of 110 beats per minute. Genetic testing confirmed a germline missense mutation at c.386T>G of the VHL gene. She has a negative family history. ACMG: PP2, PS2, PP4.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Evidence Statements: The National Cancer Institute has a frozen tumour bank of ccrenal cell carcinoma tumours that have been removed from VHL patients. One 45Y male patient with ccrenal cell carcinoma was confirmed with a germline deletion (c.525_525delA) in the VHL gene. No family history or other phenotype was provided. ACMG: PVS1
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Checked on CIViC: nomenclature confirmed - needs to be edited on CIViC. minor change to c. and p.
Evidence Statements: DNA samples of 20 members from the Chinese family with non-syndromic PCCs and 41 patients with apparently sporadic pheochromocytoma were analyzed by polymerase chain reaction and direct sequencing, confirmed by Taqman probe. A 22 year old Chinese male patient presented with unilateral pheochromocytoma. Genetic testing confirmed a familial frameshift mutation at 623insTTTTGTtG of the VHL gene. The patient has a father, mother and a sister with the same mutation, however the father and sister are asymptomatic, while the mother also presents with unilateral pheochromocytoma.
